Mobiles.LongDescription: A sleepy looking villager is here, lounging about.
Mobiles.Description: This dirtily clad man looks and smells like he could use a bath.  Hisdroopy eyes hang underneath his bushy eyebrows, giving him an almost obsceneappearance.

Mobiles.LongDescription: An ugly villager is here, running to the market.
Mobiles.Description: This man is terribly ugly and dirty!  He rushes to the market in thethought that what he has to accomplish today is actually important.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A burly fisherman stands here, waiting to unload his ship.
Mobiles.Description: Before you stands a large and very hairy man that waits to unload hisboat of the wares that he has caught during the day.  He eyes yoususpiciously, then returns to work.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A small boy stands here, hoping to learn some of the tricks of the trade.
Mobiles.Description: He is a small sandy haired youth with the exuberance that only childrenseem to possess.  He hangs around the pier so he can gain some glimpse ofwhat all the grown up men are doing.

Mobiles.ShortDescription: A guardian of the Canthi Seers
Mobiles.LongDescription: A guardian of the Sea Folk stands here, guarding the ship.
Mobiles.Description: This man does not even blink when you look at him, he is a fearsomelooking man that is not ashamed by his naked condition.  He stands right inthe way of the ramp leading on board the ship, so you'll have to get by himto do anything.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A villager stands here, surprised by your intrusion.
Mobiles.Description: The villager blinks in surprise as you enter his home?  What the hell areyou doing in here, he asks?  You almost feel bad about the incident untilyou realize that this scum is trying to steal gold from your purse!

Mobiles.LongDescription: A small child runs about here, needing a bath.
Mobiles.Description: He's just a small child looking for something to do, no more, no less.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A burly blacksmith stands here, pounding at his forge.
Mobiles.Description: This man is covered in sweat from head to toe.  His arms ripple withmuscles that can only be made from hours and hours of toil and the anvil.He blinks up at you with his bushy eyebrows and scowls only slightly, wipesthe sweat from his brow, and continues back to work.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A man is here, tending to the waterwheel.
Mobiles.Description: A man that tends to the daily ministrations of the water wheel, his darkbrown hair is wet and matted from the constant mist that pervades the room.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A Sea Folk deckhand is going about his duties here.
Mobiles.Description: This man is naked from the waist up, his muscles rippling as he goesabout his duties.  He carries a serious demeanor with him, and looks onlyslightly surprised at your intrusion onto the ship.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A female deck hand is here, naked from the waist up!
Mobiles.Description: Your eyes keep tracking down to her breasts as you stare at thiswonderfully endowed deck hand.  As you try to stuff your tongue back intoyour mouth, the deck hand moves away, and goes about her duties.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A filthy beggar is here, wallowing in his own feces.
Mobiles.Description: This man has reached the very pits of human existence.  Naheed is so filthythat the dirt is caked upon his skin in sheets, much like the bark of atree.  He is so malnourished that he does not even have the strength to lifthimself out of the feces that he lays in.  In all, he is a pathetic sight,and you long to both help him, and leave his disgusting presence.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Seth, the owner of the Salty Pork Rind, serves drinks here.
Mobiles.Description: The man who stands before you has spent too long behind the bar, and withhis treasured bottles of ale and spirits.  His gut hangs over his dirt cakedwaist line like a snowbank ready to avalanche.  He leers at you and asks youwhat you'll be drinking.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A disheveled receptionist sits here, taking down guest's names.
Mobiles.Description: Before you stands a receptionist that looks like she has had too muchwork to do over the last few days.  Her hair is in complete disarray and herclothes are a complete mess.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A check in clerk stands behind the counter here.
A villager is here, lost and quite disturbed.
Mobiles.Description: This man is quite a pathetic sight indeed, he clutches his head infrustration as he struggles to overcome his drunkeness and find his wayhome!

Mobiles.LongDescription: A pathetic squatter is here, trying to eke out an existence.
Mobiles.Description: Before you sits a filthy squatter, a life long resident of the pits ofEbon Downs.  He is an unkempt man, and looks as if the last vestiges ofself esteem left his body long ago.

Mobiles.LongDescription: The Mayor of Ebon Downs stands here, campaigning for next term.
Mobiles.Description: He is the leader of this seaport town, a man that thinks very highly ofhimself.  His gut hangs down over his belt, belying a pathetic attempt tohide the increase in weight over the years.  The added girth has given himmore resonance in his voice however, and he bellows loudly at the podium,trying to gain votes.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A man stands here, waiting to take all your valuables.
Mobiles.Description: This man has grown hard over the years, having to struggle for every biteto eat and every scrap of clothing he owns.  He has had to fight for it too,and is prepared to fight you for your posessions.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A man stands here silently, waiting to rough you up!
Mobiles.Description: Before you stands an unshaved man, dirty from the long absence from anytype of water.  He glares at you sullenly for an instance, then realizesthat you probably have a lot of cash on you.

Mobiles.LongDescription: The surly strumpet stands here, waiting both on and for her next customer.
Mobiles.Description: This lady has had her share of hardships. She struts around with an airof self importance, but you know that deep down inside, she is a seething pitof hurt, and nothing in her crub face or lean thighs can hide that fromyour all seeing eyes

Mobiles.LongDescription: A woman stands here, controlling business for her prostitutes.
Mobiles.Description: Before you stands a self assured woman who has made it in a businesstraditionally held by men.  She is a pimp!  And proud of it!  A thick redgirdle helps to keep her aging gut in, and all in all, she is quitedisgusting, but she knows her business.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A patron of the Rest sits comfortably at a table here.
Mobiles.Description: He is a man that looks like he spends much of his time here at theWayfarer's Rest.  His well worn breeches and mundane clothes mark him as aman who comes here after a day of work.  He looks tired though, and seems toenjoy his privacy.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A serving girl scuttles about here, trying to take orders.
Mobiles.Description: She is a pretty young girl with plain brown eyes and hair, that scuttlesto and fro, trying to take everyone's order, and get everyone's meal.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A man that is finished with working rests here.
Mobiles.Description: Before you stands a man that has retired from normal life, and now hastime to kick back and relax.  He sports a greying beard, and looks as if heneeds to trim his eyebrows a bit.  He looks up at you in surprise, and goesback to his drink.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A wizened Seer of the ship is here, convening a gathering of the four winds.

Mobiles.ShortDescription: First Mate of the Canthi Seers
Mobiles.LongDescription: The First Mate of the Seers ship stands here, working out.
Mobiles.Description: He is a large, burly man that glistens with sweat as he works out to getinto shape.  He is naked from the waist up, exposing his chiseled chest andstomach.  He stares back at you with steely grey eyes, and you decide thatyou would not want to mess with this man.

Mobiles.LongDescription: The Sea Folk cook stands here, preparing the next meal.
Mobiles.Description: This Sea Folk man is an aberration of the Sea Folk norm, he is quitecorpulent and does not take off his shirt like most of the other men orwomen.  He chops furiously away at onions that will go into the ship's nextmeal.  He glances up at you quickly and decides that you aren't worth thetrouble.

Mobiles.LongDescription: The Captain of the Canthi Seers pores over ocean maps here.
Mobiles.Description: This man is a dark and scowly man, scarred by the voyages across seas andoceans.  He is naked from the waist up, and seems to have no selfconsciousness in his cleanly shaved and chiseled face when you stare at hisrippling pectoral muscles.  He grins and goes back to studying his maps.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A water snake slithers menacingly in the depths here.
An adventurer is here, kicking up his heels and relaxing after a long day.
Mobiles.Description: Before you stands a gruff looking man, face covered with the stubble of abeard that has gone too long unshaved.  His scarred face covers what seemsto be a joyful and endearing personality, but nevertheless, you have walkedinto his room, and disturbed his peace!

Mobiles.LongDescription: Before you, a man with gleaming green eyes, clad in black stands idly.
Mobiles.Description: His green eyes gleam at you with a feral gaze, chilling you to the boneas you realize that this man is the very embodiment of the Shadow insideman.  A shadow keeper to the very roots of his soul.  He slicks back his jetblack hair, and licks his lips and smiles.  Gesturing you into his parlor,he snickers with the coldness of someone all knowing.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A man looks at you nervously as he clutches his robes to his body.
Mobiles.Description: This man is clad entirely in black, and stares at you with a shifty gazeas he clutches his clothing close to his body.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A villager looks up at you with surprise as you enter his home!
Mobiles.Description: He is just like any other coddled villager you have ever seen, born witha silver spoon in his mouth, and arrogant beyond all rankings.

Mobiles.LongDescription: The villager looks up with surprise at your sudden entrance!
Mobiles.Description: This woman looks up at you with surprise as you have intruded herafternoon nap!  She sneers at you with an arrogance unbecoming to anyone,and you immediately decide you do not like the woman.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A gruff and deeply tanned man is here, skinning a fish.
A woman of vigorous health is beheading some broccoli behind her counter.
A mustang rears and snorts angrily as you enter his stall.
An old man hums and whistles a tune to himself.
In port for the day, a sailor is enjoying the town's bars, drunk off his ass.
A sightless old woman walks carefully to the marketplace.
A fisherman stands here, gazing out over the water searchingly.
`aThe master assassin rests comfortably in her chair.``
Mobiles.Description: `aJericka is a tall woman, standing nearly six feet, though she can appear muchshorter when the situation calls for it.  She is thinly built, but with a leanmuscularity.  Her black hair falls to her shoulders, framing her dark face.With high cheekbones and angular facial features, she looks as though she couldhave been carved from ebony.  Her expression is generally relaxed and the calmin her eyes gives away nothing of her profession.``

Mobiles.LongDescription: `aBaldor is here for all your black market needs.``
`aA shady individual is crouching over his latest victim: a newbie with poor dodging skills.``
Mobiles.Description: `aWell, this is a shady individual, thanks to all the shadows and stuff he remains that way.``

Mobiles.LongDescription: A merchant from distant lands is standing here.
Mobiles.Description: You smell a vague scent of salty sea air mixed with a faint trace ofspices as he passes by you, giving you no more than a quick, disintrestedglance.  He wears white cotton robes, and a thick, square black beard.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A canthi boy is resting against the far wall, waiting for a customer.
An old canthi sits on a three-legged stool here, inspecting his needles.
Mobiles.Description: `gThis is old Squinty Cross-eye, the canthi pirates and sailors from farand wide come to to get their tattoos.  He peers up at you through his thickglasses, seemingly expecting something from you.  ``

Rooms.RoomDescription: `dMounds of flattened red soil are encroached by thick tufts of cloverand grass, creating a traversable, if narrow path through the area here.West- ward, the sounds of industry and civilization fill the air, and toyour east you can see a continuation of the road, leading to a flat plateauof rock.  ``

Rooms.RoomName: At the piers of Ebon Downs
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand among the long, majestic piers of Ebon Downs.  Ships rangingfrom thin, seafolk cruisers, to fat and bulky merchant river traders aredocked here, ready to unload their cargo.  Men and women alike hustle to andfro here, trying to get their business done for the day.  The main roadleading into Ebon Downs proper heads off to the north here.

As you walk steadily towards the center of Ebon Downs, the populationincreases steadily, and you are jostled about a few times by rude locals.The air here smells of stale fish, and the sound of hoarse yelling and woodbanging on wood fills the air.  The main road winds its way between numerousencampments that have sprung up around the trading of the piers.

You now stand on the main street that winds its way through the heart ofEbon Downs.  Small homes and businesses line the street to either side,busy with the influx of the trading vessels.  Just to the north of here, youcan see what appears to be the central circle of the town, dominated by awide brass fountain.  The fountain is shaped into the form of a massiveleaping fish, water spewing from both its mouth and gills.

This is the center of the entire town of Ebon Downs.  The circle offersroads that lead off in all four cardinal directions, and is dominated by amassive brass fountain that stands in the center of the circle.  Thefountain is shaped in the form of a leaping fish, water spewing from itsmouth and gills.  Truthfully, it is not a very pretty statue, but yousuppose the locals find some sort of value in it.

You walk along the main 'avenue', if you would call it that, of EbonDowns.  In reality, it is not much more than a hard-packed dirt road thathas had ruts worn in it by too many overloaded ox carts.  The road winds itsway through a series of shops and homes, sturdy, but not very affluentlooking.

The main road of Ebon Downs continues to the north and south here,making its way through a smattering of buildings that could probably be usedfor either residential use or commerce.  The buildings are made of a thinklooking wood, and looks very suited to the port type town that Ebon Downshas become to be known as.

You are on a slightly elevated plot of dirt that serves as a road thatdissects Ebon Downs in half.  For the most part, the buildings that linethe hard packed dirt are fairly old, and look as if they could use somerenovation.  High Street comes back to a normal elevation a short ways offto the west, where you can see the famous leaping fish fountain ofEbon Downs.

The main road extending through the center of Ebon Downs continues tothe north and south here.  Just to the south, you can see what appears to bethe center of town, a circle dominated by a massive brass fountain, shapedto resemble a leaping fish.  As for the buildings along the street itself,they are not immense in size, but they look fair enough for a village ofthis size.

You have arrived at the intersection between Ilangollen and Bridge Streets.Ilangollen Street has been named after the river that plies Ebon Downs'strade, although you can see no particular reason why it has been thuslycalled.  It seems like any other road in the town, hard packed dirt, and ifyou are lucky, a think sprinkling of gravel on top.  Ilangollen Street runs tothe east and west here, where you can see more buildings and shops liningthe street.

The alleyway continues onwards here, cutting through a number ofbuildings and bathing you in their shadows.  Trash litters the street, andthe stench of rotting food items assails your nose.  Off to the west here,you can see a collection of boxes that have been set up.  You can't make outwhat they are exactly in the darkness, but you can see Bridge Street offto the east.

You stand at the end of the darkened alleyway.  To the north and eaststand the back of buildings, the back doors barred and sealed shut long ago.Off to the west, you can see what all the boxes and wooden beams have beenused to construct.  It is a literal encampment of the homeless, a sulliedand bedraggled bunch of folk that make you feel both sick and sad at thesame time.  They sit under their makeshift shelters and you walk by,pretending that they don't exist.

Here among the broken down boxes and wooden planks that try to supportthe sagging structures, you can't but help find the compassionate side inyou.  There are only so many children's pouting eyes that you can look intobefore you cave in, and decide to give them a few coins.

The smell here is not a pleasant one to say the least.  It is a toxicmixture of sweat, month old dirt, and blood and urine that seeps into yournose and leaves a bad taste in your mouth.  Nevertheless, you can't help butfeel pity and compassion for the huddled creatures who are forced to dwellhere, and you think that maybe it wouldn't be a stretch to give them a fewcoins.

Ilangollen Street runs off the east here, taking a bend to the north anddisappearing shortly out of view.  The buildings lining the street here aremuch like any other you have encountered in Andor, and made of the samesturdy construction.  A short ways off to the west, you can make out whereIlangollen Street intersects with the main road, Bridge Street.

Ilangollen Street continues to run to the west here, where a short distanceoff, you can see where it intersects with yet another dirt road.  Smallhouses predominantly line this street, hugging each other wall to wall in aneffort to steal a little bit extra space.

Ilangollen Street runs off to the east and west here, bounded by a numberof small homes that are connected wall to wall.  The homes are mostly onestory in construction, cheap places that look as if they have been massproduced.  In any case, the flow of traffic on the road is light, and youcan go either way down the street.

You have arrived at the intersection of Taranel and Ilangollen.  Theintersection is not particularly busy, no more so than any otherintersection you have seen here.  Besides a few shops that sell food anddrink, the corner is bounded by homes and what appear to be office buildingsof some type.  The air here smells a bit like stale fish, and as you lookoff to the west and the Ilangollen River, you can guess why.

Taranel Road runs to the north and south here, a shady looking districtthat seems to house every overbearing and threatening looking soul in theentire town.  A short distance off to the north, the hard packed dirt roadintersects with Ilangollen Street, and off to mthe south, slopes slightlydownward to meet the intersection with the Low Road.

A small alleyway cuts in between a pair of buildings here on the mainroad of Ebon Downs.  Although the surrounding buildings are not very tallat all, they seem to cast shadows across the alleyway, even during the peakhours of the day.  Shady characters creep about around each corner here, andyou think that maybe you are wandering into a bad part of town.

The dimness of this tavern is such that it hurts your eyes.  The paradoxof that statement is lost on you as you are engulfed in the embrace of agroup of swarthy men reeking of alcohol and smoke.  The room itself is largeenough to house a good twenty round tables, and a long bar on the west endof the chamber.  The entire atmosphere is fairly seedy, and you definitelythink you would not recommend this bar to any newbie!

This room is brightly lit by enclosed lanterns that hang on either sideof the chamber.  They frame a long receptionist's desk along the east wall,where a man stands, taking reservations for rooms in the inn upstairs.  Thewalls are plainly decorated with mundane paintings of landscapes, andtrophies of fish caught in the local river.  It isn't the most exciting innthat you have ever seen, but it definitely is not the worst either.  Behindthe counter, you can see where a ladder leads the way up to the secondfloor, and to what you presume are the bedchambers.

The ladder from downstairs deposits you here in a small, cubical alcovethat is bordered by a door to each of its four sides.  A pair of lanternsprovide the lighting here, and the associated shadows are accompanied by asmell wafting through the air.  It is quite pleasant actually, and smells oflavenders blooming in the fall.

Rooms.RoomName: A bedroom at The River Bed
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand in a small cubicle of a chamber that is barely large enough tofit the bed and the dresser that exist there.  As you glance around theunadorned room, you wonder where you can go to the bathroom in this inn.  Asyou glance out the tiny window in the north wall, you realize that thebathroom is a small shack that stands a good fifty feet away from the rearof the building.

Rooms.RoomName: A bedroom at The River Bed
Rooms.RoomDescription: The room that you have walked into is a tiny cubicle, barely large enoughfor human survival.  In fact, besides the bed and the dresser in the room,you would be lucky if you could even carry your bags into the room.  Theroom is dimly lit and smells faintly of lavender and an undercurrent ofsweat.  Maybe that would explain why the innkeepers would want to burn thosescented candles...

Rooms.RoomName: A bedroom at The River Bed
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand in the doorway of a tiny room, that you can barely fit yourbuttocks into.  A bed and a dresser standing adjacent to it are thefurnishings in the room, leaving perhaps enough room to lay down your pack.The room smells faintly of sweat, and the bed sheets are littered with theoccassional piece of caked mud.

Rooms.RoomName: A bedroom at The River Bed
Rooms.RoomDescription: The lighting in this room is provided by a single flickering lantern thathangs from a hook in the ceiling.  A bed and a dresser are about the onlythings that can fit in this tiny cubicle of a room, it is disgustingly smalland actually smells a bit like breeches that have not been washed in amonth.

Rooms.RoomName: The backroom at the Salty Pork Rind
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand in the back room of The Salty Pork Rind, and at first glance,it does not appear any cleaner than the main room.  Ale has been spilledonto the ground, forming a rather odiferous stench.  Sharp looking kniveshave been jammed into the wooden walls here with great force, and byinference, you assume that this is where some of the men come to play atknives and darts.

The Low Road intersects Taranel Road here.  Although the Low Road seemsto be one of the busiest streets in Ebon Downs, this intersection itselfdoes not seem to direct much traffic.  The banks of the Ilangollen flow to thesouth and west here, making you wonder what insane builder would place thetown right along the shores of the waters.  An embankment has been built upagainst the river side, but it seems to be a tenuous position nevertheless.

You stand on a road that seems slightly depressed in comparison to themain road of Ebon Downs.  Hence, the name Low Road most likely.  In anycase, the hard packed dirt road extends off to the west here, where it meetsanother street running north and south.  Most of the buildings lining thisstreet seem to be businesses, plying their trade.  A short distance off tothe east, you can see the massive fish fountain that seems to almostcharacterize Ebon Downs.

Rooms.RoomName: On a pier at Ebon Downs
Rooms.RoomDescription: The pier under your feet seems to creak with every step you take, eventhough the wood seems to have been treated in some way.  At the end of thispier in particular, you can make out the sails of a Sea Folk cutter, itsthin hull floating majestically above the murky waters of the river below.There are no railings on the pier, and you wonder what would happen ifsomeone took the plummet down to the river below.

Rooms.RoomName: On a pier at Ebon Downs
Rooms.RoomDescription: You have reached the end of the pier, at which a Sea Folk cutter is tied.You can't make out anything inside the darkened vessel that looms to thenorth, and the slender Canthi man standing in front of the loading rampdoes not seem inclined to let you have a closer look.  Nevertheless, thesight is a majestic one.  If only you could get a peek inside...

You're not sure exactly how you fell off the pier, but you won't havemuch time to ponder the subject before you fall into the swirling river.Hopefully, you're a good swimmer and things will turn out for the best.

Rooms.RoomName: Ramp to a Sea Folk vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand on a thin wooden plank that has been placed at an angle toallow you access to the Sea Folk vessel moored at the pier.  The creakingwood of the ramp does not seem like it would support your weight, butnevertheless it does, and you can see where the ramp disappears into theship itself.  The waters of the Ilangollen River slosh underneath the ramphere, lapping up against the hull of the boat in cyclic waves.

You have walked into a small home, essentially a one room cabin.  It isquaintly decorated in sublime greens and violets, and for the staunchermasculine warrior types, it almost makes you feel sick.  Pieces of furniturehave been carefully laid around the room in an effort to maximize space andminimize the clutter.  Gently brushed portrait plates hang from the walls inbetween carefully placed reed bundles, all adding to the down home image.

You stand in a small room that has a desk planted in its center.  Behindthe desk sits a waspy faced man, eager to write down your hometown anddestination.  Other than the large oak desk, the room is unadorned, and sodrab it makes you want to vomit.

The Low Road continues both to the east and west here, cutting through abusy commercial area.  Vendors and shop owners hawk their wares here,bumping into you in an effort to get your attention.  It's almostclaustrophobic here, and you decide you want to get out of this area asquickly as possible.

The door opens up into a small front chamber bathed in a think pinklight.  The room is garishly decorated in pink and light blues, andeverything seems to be either frilly or puffy.  A number of ladies loungeabout here, waiting to pick up their next job, which might be you from thelooks of things!  An open doorway leads off to the east here, to where, yournaive mind can only wonder.

You stand just inside one of the more reputable inns in Ebon Downs, TheWayfarer's Rest.  There is nothing visibly special about the inn, exceptperhaps the fact that it is nearly spotless.  Tables of various shapes andsizes are scattered about the room, with accompanying chairs.  A bar hasbeen established a little bit further to the west here, offering theirsupply of home brew.  The atmosphere here is pleasant, and although thesmell of smoke is strong, and the conversation loud, you almost feel at homehere.

You stand in a short hallway, lit by candles burning in sconces on eachwall.  A pair of open doorways are partially obscured by silk screens bothto the north and south here.  Judging from the moaning and squeaking goingon behind the screens, you think that it might be a good idea to get out ofhere.

You have entered a room that has as furniture a single bed that rests inthe middle of the room.  The sheets on the bed are rumpled, and smell ofsweat, woman, and man.  A soft but garish lantern emanates its pink lightacross the length of the otherwise bare room, the owners of this fineestablishment spared no expense it seems.

Just beyond the silk screen is a room that is bathed in pink light, muchlike the rest of the building.  The floor is uncovered and the only piece offurniture here is a small bed in the center.  The sheets on the bed arerumpled and are stained yellow in a number of places.  All in all, the sceneis a gruesome one and you are inclined to turn around and leave.

Rooms.RoomName: The Bar at the Wayfarer's Rest
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand before a brass bar that separates you from the bartender here.Various people stand here, trying to get information, or just looking to buya mug of the Wayfarer's rest home brew.  As you peruse the selection writtenon a piece of slate behind the bar, you are taken aback at the prices of theale here.  Then again you think, money isn't always what it seems here.  Offto the south and east, you can see where tables and chairs have been set up,and to the southeast, you can see where a small area has been cleared forthe possibility of a performing gleeman.

Rooms.RoomName: The Common Room at The Wayfarer's Rest
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand amidst the tables and chairs that have been placed here in thecommon room.  Serving girls run to and fro, trying to get everyone's orderand drinks.  The floor here is remarkably clean, and like the furniture, ismade from a deep, uncracked oak.  Off to the east, you can see where ahopeful and enthusiastic audience has cleared a place for any wanderinggleeman to play.

Rooms.RoomName: The Common Room at the Wayfarer's Rest
Rooms.RoomDescription: This is the southeast corner of the common room, a bit darker than therest of the main chamber.  A small place has been cleared among the tablesand chairs here, and a slight platform has been inserted.  You can onlyassume that this is where gleeman perform when the inn has the good fortuneof obtaining one's services.

Rooms.RoomName: Sleeping Chambers at The Wayfarer's Rest
Rooms.RoomDescription: You have arrived at the top of the dimly lit staircase.  Off to thenorth, a hallway runs that ends a short ways off in a collection of threedoors.  The hallway itself is adorned with a few, rather boring paintingsthat seem to be placed there because there was simply nothing else todecorate with.  The staircase leads the way down here, back into the smokeand ruckus of the common room.

Rooms.RoomName: Sleeping Chambers at The Wayfarer's Rest
Rooms.RoomDescription: This is the end of the hallway on the second floor.  Doors made from athick, heavy wood confront you to the north, east, and west.  It is amusingto look at the architecture of the rooms, since the doors swing outwards,two people can't leave their rooms at the same time.

Before you is a small chamber, that holds a bed, a small table, a desk,and a dresser.  For the money that you have to pay to room in this inn, itis not a bad deal at all.  The walls have been thoughtfully decorated withsmall trinkets from Linden, a banner with the lions of Athanmere forexample.  A small chamberpot sits in the corner of the room, ready to befilled.

You stand in a small bedroom here in the Wayfarer's Rest.  A small bedstands against the back of the room, framed on either side by a dresser andtable.  All in all, the room is pretty nondescipt, cozy, but not with anyextravagant features.  A chamberpot sits in the corner of the room as well,saving you a trip to the outhouse that smells up the street outside.

This is a small bedroom that you stand in.  It contains a smallish bed, adresser, and most importantly, a brass chamberpot that smells of freshlypruned hedges.  The walls of the room have been decorated with variousbanners from various provinces, ranging from Promeria, to that the grandcapital of Thesden itself.

You stand in a dark alleyway that extends off to the north here,enshrouded in darkness and debris.  Shady looking characters pace back andforth here and lounge against the building walls, in anticipation of atraveler walking alone.  The air smells of week old rotting meat, andassails your nostrils with the force of a sledge hammer driving a nail intoyour nose.  It is sickening, and you decide you probably don't want to stayhere much longer.

You have arrived at an intersection in the alleyway, that allows you tohead either east or west.  The alleyway ends a short ways off to the east,in a pile of rubble and broken wooden beams.  Off to the west, you can see aworn down looking door, wood grey from water damage and general old age.The building to which the door leads is delapidated looking.  You are amazedthat it can stand on its own.

Rooms.RoomName: A dead end in the alleyway
Rooms.RoomDescription: You have arrived at a dead end in the alley here.  A building that wasnot maintained very well has collapsed in front of you, and its bricks andsupporting trusses have been strewn across the alleyway.  Garbage has beenintermixed among the debris, making the entire situation one in which youwant to get out of.

You stand before a rickety looking house, mauled with the passing ofyears and the damage from the elements.  The door that leads into thebuilding is grey and worn, but somehow still looks strong, reinforced byblack steel bars placed across its width.  The windows of the building havebeen boarded shut, though you thought you could see eyes watching youthrough cracks in the slats.

Rooms.RoomName: On a ship of the Canthi Seers
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand on the main deck of the boat, at the edge where a ramp leadsdown to the pier of Ebon Downs.  The deck seems to be made of a deepdarkened wood, cured and treated so it shines with a peculiar glossy finish.The main deck continues off to the north, east.  And west, and a thin ropeladder allows you to climb up into the crow's nest.

The deck sways slightly under your feet as it adjusts for the swells thatcome into Ebon Downs off the Ilangollen River.  However, the grippy textureof the deck enables you to keep your balance easily.  It is a wonder thatthe deck offers such a foothold because at first glance, it appears to be aslippery sheen of wood/ice.  Ropes and boxes litter the deck, as the SeaFolk prepare for their next trading port-of-call.

You stand on the deck of a ship of the Canthi Seers, the fabled SeaFolk.  It's a wonder that you have made it this far onto the vessel, withall the mysteries that they keep and all.  The wood of the ship is a deepbrownish black hue, and does not contain the normal grains that you expectout of wood.  Also, despite its glossy appearance, the deck provides analmost tacky gripping for your feet to dig in, even among the wetenbironment of the high seas.

This is the main deck of the Sea Folk ship.  The wood of the deck seemsto be made of some material you have never seen before, a deep blackishbrown hue that almost does not seem like wood at all.  Although it shineswith a primordal gleam, it offers the solid foothold necessary when sailingon the high seas.

You stand at the corner of the main deck here.  A space has been clearedamong the numerous lines and boxes on the deck for the ladder that leads upto the foredeck.  The ladder looks spindly, and you doubt that it could holdyour weight.  As you look over the edge of the boat, you can see thebeautiful bends of the Ilangollen River, as it bends away towards Thesden toone side, and Promeria to the other.  The sight is an inspiring one, but youthink that if you stand on this rocking boat much longer, you may have tovomit.

You stand on the main deck of a Sea Folk trading clipper, a sleek andwell designed boat that is capable of cutting through any height of wave andwater.  The deck itself is made of a brownish black wood that grips yourfeet despite the slippery appearance.  At first glance, ropes and variousnets and boxes have been strewn haphazardly across the deck, but on closerinspection, everything is within easy reach, and filed according to theirfunctions.

Rooms.RoomName: A Hallway in a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: This is a quaintly set up hallway in the center of the Sea Folk ship,deep brown wooden panels brightly lit up by softly muted lanterns that glowalong both the walls and from the ceiling.  There are doors to the southwest and east here, presumably to what are the bedding chambers of the crew.The doors to the east and west require you to walk a bit further down thehallway though.

Rooms.RoomName: A Hallway in a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand at the western end of a nicely set up hallway inside theAtha'an Miere ship.  Doors made from the same deep brown wooden paneling asthe hallway stand both to the west and south here.  The doors themselves areslightly reinforced with bars of black steel that run across their middles.The entire scene makes you feel at home for some reason, a very comfortableand pleasing ambience.

Rooms.RoomName: A Hallway in a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: You have arrived at the eastern end of the hallway here.  Softly glowinglanterns provide a sublime lighting that emphasizes the smoothness of thewooden panels on the walls, and the artistic construction of the doorsstanding to your east and south.  The doors are reinforced with bands ofblack steel riveted across their middles, but the bands do little to lessenthe comfortable atmosphere that is present here.

Rooms.RoomName: The Hold of a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand in the hold of the Sea Folk vessel, a dark and dank chamberthat is dominated by the sheer number of boxes and chests that have beensecured to the walls and the ground here.  Dim, flickering lanterns casttheir shadows across the low ceilinged hold, making you duck and creep inthe slosh of water at your feet.  Small cracks of light seep in through therifts of a trap door that sits closed above your head here.

Rooms.RoomName: The Hold of a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand in the dark and damp hold of the ship, complete with themildewy smell and think layer of water covering the floorboards.  Youweren't sure if you expected something different, this being a Sea Folk shipand all, but nevertheless, it is nothin special.  A darkened large room thatis lit by the only occassional lantern carefully hooded on the walls.  It isquite hard to see down here, and you thought you felt something brushagainst your leg.

Rooms.RoomName: The Hold of a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand in a room that is dark and humid as well.  A thin layer ofwater sloshes about your feet, lapping over the chests and boxes that havebeen secured to the ground and to the walls.  You hope those chests arewaterproof!  Shadows play across your vision as the lanterns on the wallsflicker on and off, on and off.  You are somewhat disappointed by the entirescene, you somehow expected more from the Sea Folk.

Rooms.RoomName: The Hold of a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: This is the darkest and wettest corner of the storage hold.  Water seemsto flow in this direction, soaking you up to your ankles.  The chests andboxes strapped to the floor here have been almost completely covered, youhope for the Sea Folk's sake that they are waterproof.  Small lanternsprovide the illumniation for the hold, casting their shadows across thearea, and making the entire ambience rather ghostly.

Rooms.RoomName: The Hold of a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand in the hold of a murky and dim Sea Folk ship.  Shadows playacross your face and arms as the tiny lanterns fastened to the walls flickerback and forth.  A number of chests and boxes clutter the area here,fastened to the walls and floor with strong looking rope.  Somehow, you areprofoundly disappointed with how the hold looks, you expected more from thelegendary Sea Folk.

Rooms.RoomName: The Hold of a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand in the storage hold of the Sea Folk ship, somehow you expectedit to look differently.  It is dark and the humidity causes perspiration toimmediately form on your face.  A thin layer of water covers the floor here,lapping up to and over the chests and boxes that have been secured to thewalls and floors here.  In all, the scene is not impressive, and becomeseven less so when you feel something brush up against your leg.

Rooms.RoomName: A cabin in a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: This room is small relative to any normal room in a normal house in anormal land.  However, when you think of where you stand, in a boat, youthink that this mush be a sumptuous quarter indeed.  The room is largeenough to fit in the swinging hammock in the corner, and a number of metalfoot lockers.  The room itself is contructed from the same demure wood aswas used outside in the hallway.  Light is provided from small balls thathang from the ceiling, glowing with a soft light.

Rooms.RoomName: A cabin in a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: The doorway opens up into a smallish looking chamber that is made fromthe same soft wooden material as the paneling outside in the hallway.  Asingle glowing ball hanging from the ceiling provides the illumination inthe room, casting its soft light to each corner of the room.  A hammockswings slowly to and fro in one corner of the room, while a small dresseroccupies another corner.  It has been quaintly done, and does not have verymuch in the way of furnishings.

Rooms.TpMsg: The captain shares his ocean maps with you. Your experience increases by 100 points.
Rooms.RoomDescription: This room is at the very center of the majestic Canthi ship.  As you stepthrough the doorway, the room opens up into a spacious bowl, slightlydepressed at the center, where a full sized bed rests, bolted tightlyagainst the floor.  All around the walls of the room, paintings and ornatetapestries hang from golden rods strung across the ceiling.  Other variouspieces of furniture lie around here, everything secured to the ground bybolts and small clasps.  It is a beautiful room, especially inside a ship asit is.

Rooms.RoomName: A cabin in a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand in yet another cabin in the ship of the Canthi Seers.  It islike the other rooms you have been in before, small with a hammock in onecorner and a dresser rounding out the furnishings.  The light is provided bya small ball that hangs from the ceiling, illuminating the deep brown woodenpaneling that graces the room.

Rooms.RoomName: A cabin in a Sea Folk Vessel
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand in a small room that is made from the same soft, deep brownwood that the panels in the hallway are made from.  A single large glowingball hangs suspended from a fine wire from the ceiling, providing theillumination in the room.  A hammock has been strung up between two poles inone of he corners, the rest of the room is spent by pieces of furniture andother basic living utilities.

You cling tenunously to the rope ladder that wavers in the wind andswings with your every weight shift.  You wonder about the craziness of theCanthis and their refusal to stabilize this rope ladder.  You takecomfort only in the fact that it is a shorter fall than it is to climb tothe top.  And a small comfort that is.

You continue your perilous ascent up the rope ladder and consideryourself lucky that you have gotten even this far.  The wind shear isterrible, and you feel as if your limbs are being torn from your body.  Butyou might as well continue, because the crow's nest of the ship is only ashort ways upwards.

Phew!  At last you are out of the danger of the dangling rope ladder, andinto the relatively sheltered confines of the crow's nest.  However, afteryou sit here and rest for a moment, you realize that the entire mast isswaying in the heavy winds blowing from inland.  You start to think thatalthough the view from here is stunning, it wasn't such a great idea afterall.

You stand in a small building, essentially one large room that rings withthe sound of a hammer clanging on an anvil.  A blaze of a furnace is littowards the back of the room, further fed by a foot worked bellow.  Variousmetal workings hang from the walls here, ranging from horse shoes to poorlycrafted swords.

You stand on a slightly raised part of the vessel's deck, constructed ofthe same material as the main deck.  Off a short ways to the east, you cansee where a small steering wheel has been fastened to the rail of the ship,also made form the same brownish black wood.  A frail looking ladder leadsthe way down to the main deck here as well.

You stand on the foredeck of the Canthi Seers' ship, elevated slightlyfrom the main deck and accessible through the ladder that you have justclimbed up.  The foredeck all in all is very similar to the main deck exceptfor the fact that the clutter of the main deck does not exist here.  Also,you can see that at the very point of the ship, a disc shaped wheel has beenfastened to the railing, presumably the steering mechanism for this ship.

You stand at the very tip of the Sea Folk ship, at the point where thehelmsman steers the boat with the small disc of a wheel that has beenfastened to the railing of the ship.  You can see almost directly down ontothe water from here, and it gives you the feeling that at the first oceanswell, you will fall out of the boat.  The view must be magnificent though.

You stand on the elevated foredeck of the ship, constructed from the samebrownish black wood as the rest of the vessel.  In contrast to the main deckbelow, the foredeck is clear of any type of debris, as the helmsman surelyneeds room to maneuver.  The view off the ship here is magnificent, as youcan look almost directly down upon the water.  It gives you the feeling ofbeing suspended in mid air, and a feeling of nausea as well.

People run to and fro here, as they race each other to buy the freshestfruits and vegetables that the market has to offer.  The smell of freshlypicked greens permeates through the air, and you decide that you might wantto go ahead and buy something.  Or steal something, since that's what itseems everyone else is doing.

This is perhaps one of the more important shops in the entireEbon Downs, as it helps to promote one of its most major industries,fishing.  All sorts of hooks and lines hang from the walls here, and theentire place smells peculiarly of fish and seafood.  A seedy looking manlooks at you from behind a counter on the east wall, waiting to service you.

The sound of rushing water is almost deafening here, as the rushingcurrent of the Ilangollen River spins the massive wooden wheel in front ofyou.  The spray of water patters against your face, if you let it, it willsoak you through in no time.  You aren't sure what is done with the wheel asit turns, but then again, you never were an electrical engineer.

The stench of horse dung is overpowering as you walk into the stableshere at Ebon Downs.  Hay that has gone green with age and rot litters theground as well as the intermixed droppings of horses.  A number of not sofine animals stand in stalls here, and you think that it is no wonderEbon Downs is known as a port town, and not for their horses.

You stand just inside a small house, plainly decorated and quite boringin fact.  The vast majority of homes in Ebon Downs look almost exactly likethis one.  Sturdy wood, sparse furnishings, and just a general feeling ofunkemptness.

You stand just inside a small house in Ebon Downs.  The walls are madefrom sturdy wood and have been painted a plain white, matching the almostplain and boring charisma of this town.  The furnishings are sparse as well,consisting of a bed, dresser, and a few other minor amenities.  All in all,the home is fairly boring, much like the population of the town.

This is yet another small house in Ebon Downs.  The walls are made fromthe typical sturdy wood of Ebon Downs, and also typically boring with itssparse furnishings and unadorned walls.  It gives you the feeling of livingin a shelter made for refugees, a generic home made quickly in a time ofneed.

You have entered a large, spacious chamber that opens up on both sides,and contains rows and rows of plain wooden benches.  A podium has beenerected at the front of the room, presumably for speakers to project theirvoices better.  The walls are adorned with the portraits of the famouspeople of Ebon Downs, evidently they were not too famous, because you havenever heard of them before.  A hole has been cut in the ceiling and replacedwith glass in this room, allowing sunlight to add to the already brightlylit room.

Rooms.RoomName: How the hell did you get here?

Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand in a darkened hallway in the house, an unadorned passage thatseems to swallow up your light.  The hallway continues off to the west, andopens up into the foyer through the secret door to the east.

You stand in a darkened hallway that runs off to the east and west.There is absolutely no lighting here at all, you would have to be familiarwith the area to walk through here without any difficulty at all.  A largeoaken doorr stands slightly ajar to the west here, hiding who knows what.

You stand in a darkened room, littered with empty food containers and anumber of other wastes.  It smells stale in here, perhaps due to the factthat there is no ventilation anywhere to be found.  A small table is theonly furnishing of the room, covered with a collection of books and maps.This is the hideout for the criminal element in town, darkfriends and normalruffians alike.  A door off to the east stands slightly ajar, you can seewhere it leads off into a darkened hallway beyond the door.

You stand on top a thick metal grating, through which you can look downupon the entrance to the house.  In case you are not too perceptive, thisallows you to rain fire and acid, and arrows down upon potential intruders.It is dark here, as dark as the hallway below.  The grating has hinges thatopen up to the left, and a thin wire ladder that leads back down to thehallway below.

You find yourself floating lazily along the Ilangollen River, buoyed by itsrippling white currents, racing through the clean cut banks of the river.You find that although you are buoyed above the currents, you are beingsoaked through to the skin, and the water is cold!

Rooms.RoomName: At the end of a pier
Rooms.RoomDescription: The pier under your feet seems to creak with every step you take, eventhough the wood seems to have been treated in some way.  Close by to thenortheast, the distinctive mast and sails of a Sea Folk cutter can be seen,with its thin hull floating majestically above the murky waters of the riverinlet below.  There are no railings on the pier, and you wonder what wouldhappen if someone took the plummet down to the river below.

Rooms.RoomName: On a pier at Ebon Downs
Rooms.RoomDescription: The pier under your feet seems to creak with every step you take, eventhough the wood seems to have been treated in some way.  Close by to thenorthwest, the distinctive mast and sails of a Sea Folk cutter can be seen,with its thin hull floating majestically over the murky waters of the riverinlet below.  There are no railings on the pier, and you wonder what wouldhappen if someone took the plummet down to the river below.

You have reached a bend in the Ilangollen River here, as it curves gentlyto the east.  The waters themselves are anything but gentle though, as therapids buffet you and toss you about the width of the river.  You can seethe town of Ebon Downs overlooking the river off to the east, you wonder ifanyone in town would be willing to help you out.

The Ilangollen River runs to the south of the town of Ebon Downs here, itsrapids directing you to the south and downstream.  You are already soakedthrough, and you can only think of getting out of these chilly waters assoon as possible.

Rooms.RoomName: On the Outskirts of Ebon Downs
Rooms.RoomDescription: You come down off the Ebon Downs itself, and can see the town propernestled cozily up against the river bend up ahead.  The road you travel onnow is hard packed dirt, and little seems to change as you enter the town.The road winds its way east, into the small homes and businesses that havebeen erected along the river.  All in all, the town is nothing amazing,especially in view of the dazzling bridge just to its west.

High Street continues both to the east and west here.  Off to the east,you can see where it merges to become the Eastern Road, on its way to thefabled city of Promeria.  The High Road has gotten its name because the hardpacked dirt that you stand on seems to have been lumped over time and timeagain, and has thus become higher than the surrounding terrain.  Thebuildings on either side of High Street look fairly old, and it makesEbon Downs look pretty shabby from this perspective.

Rooms.RoomName: On the Outskirts of Ebon Downs
Rooms.RoomDescription: You stand on the outskirts of the town called Ebon Downs, a collectionof small businesses, homes, and most importantly, a port town.  The EasternRoad winds its way through small homes and the occasional shack on its wayinto the city proper.  As you walk towards the city, you notice that theelevation is getting slightly higher, as the perspective on the surroundingterrain changes.  In any case, Ebon Downs is just off to the west, as isthe Ilangollen River, so you may as well have a looksee.

You find yourself ascending as you travel a path that skirts thesunbleached cliffs of Ebon Downs.  The rocks that you climb have beenbleached a crystalized white by the unrelentless sun.  The interminableocean swells and forths beneath you to the south and the east.

You take extra care to monitor your footing as the path you travel is nolonger a real path.  Instead, you find yourself climbing the marbelizedrocks that make up this cliff face, all the while enjoying the beautifulview that this altitude is affording you.

Rooms.RoomName: On a pier at Ebon Downs
Rooms.RoomDescription: The pier under your feet seems to creak with every step you take, eventhough the wood seems to have been treated in some way.  Nearby to thenorthwest, the distinctive mast and sails of a Sea Folk cutter can be seen,with its thin hull floating majestically above the murky waters of the riverinlet below.  There are no railings on the pier, and you wonder what wouldhappen if someone took the plummet down to the river below.

The view from this incline is spectacular, with the ocean stretched outbefore you in three directions.  Looking down below, you can see thewhitewater created by angry waves pummeling the side of the cliffs.

You stand at the pinnacle of these gleaming sunbleached cliffs.  Batteredover time by sun and sea, the surface of these rocks are smooth andedgeless.  The ocean stretches out before you, an endless wave of ceruleanblue.  Looking down, you see a small cove that you think you might be ableto reach by scaling the cliff face, though you take great precaution for onefalse move could send you smashed against the rock face.

Clinging to the side of the rock face with all your might, it becomesevident why locals call this place Dead Man's Cove.  Completely unprotectedfrom the ocean and weather, this easternmost point of exposed land suffersthe brutality of vicious wind and unrelentless waves.  To the west, you spya cave entrance, though you can't tell from here how deep it goes.  You canalso attempt to scale the cliffs above, and see what lays above ground.

Rooms.RoomName: On a pier at Ebon Downs
Rooms.RoomDescription: The pier under your feet seems to creak with every step you take, even thoughthe wood seems to have been treated in some way.  Far to the west, thedistinctive mast and sails of a Sea Folk cutter can be seen, with its thinhull floating majestically over the murky waters of the river inlet below.There are no railings on the pier, and you wonder what would happen if someonetook the plummet down to the river below.

`aAs you walk further onth the darkness of the alley, the sounds of thecity fade away behind you.  It is clear that you have entered a part of thealley where few citizens dare to tread, as evidenced by the rather abruptdropoff in the litter lying around.  The wind howls around you, blowing theoccasional scrap of paper across your feet.  You may retreat back towardsthe safety of the town to your south, or continue down this alley as itturns eastward.  ``

`aThe alley takes a turn to the south here, wrapping itself around wallthat lies to the southwest, almost as though the wall was built for the solepurpose of hiding what is on this side of it.  A simple doorway in the northwall leads to a room beyond.  The garbage-strewn alley you initially passedthrough was clearly nothing more than a ruse, because this part of the alleyis immaculate.  ``

The alley comes to an end here, most likely because there wassimply noobvious reason for it to continue.  The only physical exit is to the north,where the alleyway turns west out of sight.  You are surrounded by walls inall other directions.  The only noteworthy fixture in this room also happensto be one of the most remarkable fixtures you have ever seen.  A massiveportal in the shape of a circle, ten feet across takes up the entire southwall.  Within it is a maelstrom of swirling grey mists.  The portal looks asthough it has been here for quite some time and it looks very stable.

You find yourself in a comfortable room adorned in a simple, yetrespectable fashion.  The obsidian floor has been polished to a mirrorfinish and you gaze down into it to see a shadowy reflection of yourself.Along the walls, torches have been mounted to cast a soft glow on the room.The only exit is by means of a doorway to the south.  In the middle of thenorth wall sits an overstuffed leather chair.  This room is the shrine ofthe master assassin, and it's where assassins come to be educated in theways of killing.

`bThis is the tattoo parlor, the place you want to go if you want to scaryour skin for the rest of your life.  Pictures of various tattoos hang onthe walls, everything from pretty little birds to nude women in compromisingposes.`````bA sign placed on the counter reads: '`kTATTOOS ARE PERMANENT`b'``
`aSmoke whirls around this dimly lit room as you enter, a small candleflutters on a table next to an old canthi - probably the owner of this shop.

Objects.Name: small iron bed

Objects.Name: daybed couch white

Objects.Name: rocking chair old wooden
